In computer science, a tagged union is a data structure used to hold a
value that could take on several different, but fixed, types.

Mathematically, tagged unions correspond to disjoint unions, usually
written using +. Given an element of a disjoint union 𝐴+𝐵, it is
possible to determine whether it came from 𝐴 or from the other type.

■ Description

Like option types, tagged unions can be used to handle errors via a
monad with the following functions:

fmap: (𝐴→ 𝐵)→ ((𝐴+𝐸)→ (𝐵+𝐸))=𝑓↦ 𝑎↦ {err 𝑒 if 𝑎=err 𝑒; value ( 𝑓 𝑎′ ) if
𝑎=value 𝑎′
